        'Source: https://routledgesoc.com/profile/michel-foucault\nTitle: Michel Foucault | Social Theory Rewired: New Connections to Classical and Contemporary Perspectives\nContent: Key Concepts\n\nDiscourse\n\nFoucault was interested in the phenomenon of discourse throughout his career, primarily in how discourses define the reality of the social world and the people, ideas, and things that inhabit it. For Foucault, a discourse is an institutionalized way of speaking or writing about reality that defines what can be intelligibly thought and said about the world and what cannot. For example, in The History of Sexuality, Foucault argued that a new discourse of "sexuality" had fundamentally changed the way we think about desire, pleasure, and our innermost selves. In Foucault’s argument, discourses about sexuality did not discover some pre-existing, core truth about human identity, but rather created it through particular practices of power/knowledge (see next entry).\n\nPower/Knowledge\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://routledgesoc.com/profile/michel-foucault\nTitle: Michel Foucault | Social Theory Rewired: New Connections to Classical and Contemporary Perspectives\nContent: Governmentality and Biopower\n\nIn his later work, Foucault coined the now influential concept of governmentality. According to Foucault, governmentality is the “art of governing,” not simply at the level of state politics, as we generally think of it, but the governing of a wide array of objects and persons such as entire populations at the most abstract level and one’s own desires and thoughts at a more micro level.\xa0 Foucault was especially interested in how, in contemporary times, the governing of conduct was increasingly focused on the management of populations. Unlike disciplinary power aimed at the training of individual bodies, the management of populations relied on biopower, understood as the policies and procedures that manage births, deaths, reproduction, and health and illness within the larger social body.\n\nWriting out Loud\n\nInteractive Reading\n\nHow Foucault Matters Today\n '
        ''
        'Source: https://sociology.institute/sociological-theories-concepts/foucault-genealogy-power-beyond-surface/\nTitle: Foucault\'s Genealogy: Power Beyond the Surface • Sociology Notes by Sociology.Institute\nContent: Foucault’s Genealogy: Power Beyond the Surface\n\nMichel Foucault’s genealogical writings mark a transformative shift in his work, offering a profound critique of how power operates beneath the surface of society. By delving into the intersections of social, political, and economic institutions, Foucault’s genealogy explores how power shapes individuals and structures our modern world. In this blog, we’ll unpack the concept of genealogy, understand how it differs from his earlier archaeological method, and examine key works like Discipline and Punish to understand the mechanisms of disciplinary power.\n\nTable of Contents\n\nUnderstanding genealogy in Foucault’s work 🔗\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://sociology.institute/sociological-theories-concepts/foucault-genealogy-power-beyond-surface/\nTitle: Foucault\'s Genealogy: Power Beyond the Surface • Sociology Notes by Sociology.Institute\nContent: Implications of Foucault’s genealogy 🔗\n\nFoucault’s genealogical writings challenge us to rethink power as something far more complex and dispersed than a simple top-down model. Power is not confined to governments or rulers; it is everywhere, embedded in the very fabric of society. This perspective has far-reaching implications:\n\nConclusion 🔗\n\nMichel Foucault’s genealogical writings provide a powerful lens to understand how power operates beyond the surface, shaping individuals and institutions in profound ways. By examining historical processes and everyday practices, Foucault uncovers the subtle, pervasive mechanisms of control that govern modern society. Works like Discipline and Punish offer invaluable insights into the dynamics of power-knowledge and its impact on the human body and identity.\n\nWhat do you think? How do you see power operating in your daily life? Can Foucault’s ideas help us rethink the way we engage with societal norms and institutions?\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://systemicsustainability.wordpress.com/2025/01/07/michel-foucault-in-the-modern-context/\nTitle: Michel Foucault in the Modern Context – Systemic Sustainability\nContent: Systemic Sustainability\n\nSolutions Not Delusions\n\nMichel Foucault in the Modern\xa0Context\n\nMichel Foucault, one of the most influential philosophers and social theorists of the twentieth century, made significant contributions to fields such as philosophy, sociology, history, cultural studies, and critical theory.\n\nBorn on October 15, 1926, in Poitiers, France, Paul-Michel Foucault was raised in a middle-class family with a strong academic orientation. He pursued his education at the prestigious École Normale Supérieure in Paris, where he studied philosophy and psychology. Foucault’s academic journey was marked by his deep engagement with the works of existentialists, structuralists, and historians of ideas, all of which shaped the trajectory of his intellectual development.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://systemicsustainability.wordpress.com/2025/01/07/michel-foucault-in-the-modern-context/\nTitle: Michel Foucault in the Modern Context – Systemic Sustainability\nContent: Foucault’s analysis of power-knowledge relationships is also a cornerstone of his work.\n\nHe argued that knowledge is not independent of power but is instead, a key instrument through which power operates. Discourses, or systems of knowledge and language, establish what is considered valid or true, thereby enabling the exercise of power. Foucault’s genealogical method, as demonstrated in works like “Nietzsche, Genealogy, History”, traces the historical development of these discourses, uncovering their contingent and often arbitrary nature.\n\nFoucault’s later works focused on the concepts of subjectivity and ethics.\n\nHe examined how individuals are shaped by power and discourse but also how they can resist these forces through practices of the self. In his “History of Sexuality” series, particularly “The Use of Pleasure” and “The Care of the Self”, Foucault explored how ancient Greek and Roman philosophies provided models for ethical self-fashioning.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://sociology.institute/sociological-theories-concepts/foucault-genealogy-power-beyond-surface/\nTitle: Foucault\'s Genealogy: Power Beyond the Surface • Sociology Notes by Sociology.Institute\nContent: Key features of Foucault’s genealogical method 🔗\n\nGenealogy vs. archaeology: A methodological shift 🔗\n\nFoucault’s earlier works, particularly in The Archaeology of Knowledge, focused on archaeology as a method for analyzing the rules and structures that govern knowledge production. Archaeology examines how discourses emerge and organize knowledge systems. While archaeology emphasizes the structural aspects of knowledge, genealogy shifts the focus to power and its role in shaping both knowledge and society.\n\nThe key distinction lies in their scope:\n\nThis methodological evolution allowed Foucault to move beyond a structural analysis of knowledge and into the dynamic, relational field of power, shedding light on how institutions like prisons, schools, and hospitals shape individuals.\n\nDisciplinary power: The making of the modern individual 🔗\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://polsci.institute/understanding-political-theory/foucault-genealogy-power-discourse-discipline/\nTitle: Foucault\'s Genealogy of Power: Discourse and Discipline • PolSci Institute\nContent: Foucault’s Genealogy of Power: Discourse and Discipline\n\nWhen we think about power, we often imagine politicians, laws, and governments. But what if power is more pervasive, intricate, and embedded in our everyday lives than we realize? Michel Foucault, the French philosopher, redefined our understanding of power through his groundbreaking concepts of discourse, archaeology, and genealogy. He delved into institutions like prisons and asylums to reveal how power operates subtly yet effectively, shaping societies and individuals alike.\n\nTable of Contents\n\nUnraveling discourse: The power of words 🔗\n\nAt the heart of Foucault’s analysis is the concept of discourse. But what exactly is discourse? In simple terms, discourse refers to the ways in which knowledge and truth are constructed through language and practices. It’s more than just words; it’s the entire system of thoughts, beliefs, and norms that influence how we perceive and interact with the world.\n\nSource: https://systemicsustainability.wordpress.com/2025/01/07/michel-foucault-in-the-modern-context/\nTitle: Michel Foucault in the Modern Context – Systemic Sustainability\nContent: Instead, Foucault emphasized that power is also productive, shaping norms, identities, and desires ala Edward Bernays. His examination of sexuality challenged the idea that it had been suppressed in modern society, instead arguing that sexuality had become a central focus of scientific discourse and state intervention, and while this argument may be debated, it may also indicate that the modern disruption surrounding gender and sexuality is not necessarily a random, evolutionary process of societal norms.\n\nFoucault’s analysis of power-knowledge relationships is also a cornerstone of his work.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://systemicsustainability.wordpress.com/2025/01/07/michel-foucault-in-the-modern-context/\nTitle: Michel Foucault in the Modern Context – Systemic Sustainability\nContent: Foucault’s insights, when adapted within a modern context and made available and understandable or relatable to the average person, offer practical and important lessons for fostering individual agency and critical consciousness. This is especially relevant in modern society, which is increasingly shaped by centralized power structures, engineered narratives, and the interplay between subjective and objective truths.\n\nFoucault argued that power is not solely repressive but also productive, meaning it shapes identities, desires, and norms. This dual nature of power creates opportunities for resistance. Foucault’s concept of “practices of the self” refers to the ways individuals can cultivate ethical self-awareness and exercise agency within power structures through civic participation.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://sociology.institute/sociological-theories-concepts/foucault-genealogy-power-beyond-surface/\nTitle: Foucault\'s Genealogy: Power Beyond the Surface • Sociology Notes by Sociology.Institute\nContent: Table of Contents\n\nUnderstanding genealogy in Foucault’s work 🔗\n\nGenealogy, as Foucault describes it, is a method of historical analysis that focuses on the origins and evolution of ideas, practices, and institutions. Rather than assuming a linear progression or a singular truth, genealogy uncovers the messy, contingent, and often contradictory processes through which power operates. Drawing inspiration from Nietzsche’s concept of genealogy, Foucault emphasizes that history is not a march toward progress but a battlefield where power struggles and conflicting forces shape societal norms.\n\nFor Foucault, genealogy is about understanding “how” power works rather than “why.” It examines the emergence of societal norms, institutions, and practices to reveal the hidden mechanisms of control. This method rejects grand narratives, focusing instead on localized and contextual histories to demonstrate how power is dispersed and embedded in the fabric of everyday life.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://genealogiesofmodernity.org/journal/2021/6/8/what-foucault-meant\nTitle: Genealogies of Modernity — What Foucault Meant When He Said “Genealogy”\nContent: In stressing possibility, I am emphasizing an underdeveloped dimension of Foucault’s analysis of pouvoir, or power, as it usually appears in English translations of his work. As Philipp Rosemann reminded me, pouvoir has more semantic overlap with the Latin virtus than it does with the English power. Less a force against an object, or force made structure, as Derrida once defined it, Foucault’s pouvoir is capacity or capability to do something; pouvoir is capability made possible by contingency.\n\nIt is common to describe Foucault’s genealogy as a campaign dedicated to unmasking the will to power by revealing institutions’ bad-faith assertions of noble origins. My charitable reading suggests another aspect of genealogy, a hermeneutic of historical contingency oriented to limit cases when new capabilities can emerge through different relations within and among institutions, communities, and individuals. This Foucault is not only critical but also constructive, creative.\n '
        ''
        'Source: https://www.britannica.com/biography/Michel-Foucault\nTitle: Michel Foucault | French Philosopher, Historian & Social Theorist | Britannica\nContent: What did Michel Foucault write?\nMichel Foucault began to attract wide notice as one of the most original and controversial thinkers of his day with the appearance of\xa0The Order of Things in 1966. His best-known works included Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison (1975) and The History of Sexuality, a multivolume history of Western sexuality.\n\n'
        ''
        'Source: https://www.britannica.com/biography/Michel-Foucault/Foucaults-ideas\nTitle: Michel Foucault - Philosopher, Postmodernism, Power | Britannica\nContent: Table of Contents\nTable of Contents Ask the Chatbot\nQuick Facts\nIn full:\nPaul-Michel Foucault\n(Show\xa0more)\nBorn:\nOctober 15, 1926, Poitiers, France\n(Show\xa0more)\nDied:\nJune 25, 1984, Paris (aged 57)\n(Show\xa0more)\nSubjects Of Study:\nmental disorder\nprison\nsexuality\nsociety\n(Show\xa0more)\nOn the Web:\nBBC Sounds - Thinking Allowed - Michel Foucault - a special programme on his work and influence. (Mar. 26, 2025)\n(Show\xa0more)\nSee all related content\n\n'
